<font color="#FF0000">SAVIN' FACE</font><br>
<tt>Sat Apr 26  1:27:44 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
I was surprised in 1975 when the newspapers said that the US had lost the war with the fall of Saigon.  I thought the war was over for the US in  January 1973 with the signing of  the Agreement on Ending the War and Restoring Peace in Vietnam. <br><br>
************************************<br>
Taken from the &quot;Peace with Honor&quot;; Radio-television broadcast with President Nixon: <br>
 <br><br>
Throughout the years of negotiations, we have insisted on peace with honor.  In my addresses to the Nation from this room of January 25 and May 8, 1972,  I set forth the goals that we considered essential for peace with honor.<br><br>
In the settlement that has now been agreed to, all the conditions that I laid down then have been met.  A cease-fire, internationally supervised, will begin at 7pm, this Saturday,  January 27, Washington time.  Within 60 days from this Saturday all Americans held prisoners of war throughout Indochina will be released.  There will be the fullest possible accounting for all of those who are missing in action.<br><br>
During the same 60-day period, all American forces will be withdrawn from South Vietnam.<br><br>
The people of South Vietnam have been guaranteed the right to determine their own future, without outside interference.<br><br>
By joint agreement, the full text of the agreement and the protocols to carry it out, will be issued tomorrow.<br><br>
Throughout these negotiations we have been in the closest consultation with President Thieu and other representative of the Republic of Vietnam.  this settlement meets the goals and has the full support of President Thieu and the Government of the Republic of Vietnam, as well as that of our other allies who are affected.<br><br>
The United States will continue to recognize the Government of the Republic of Vietnam as the sole legitimate government of South Vietnam.<br><br>
We shall continue to aid South Vietnam within the terms of the agreement and we shall support efforts by the people of South Vietnam to settle their problems peacefully  among themselves.<br><br>
We must recognize that ending the war is only the first step toward building the peace.  All parties must now see to it that this is a peace that lasts, and also a peace that heals, and a peace that not only ends the war in Southeast Asia, but contributes to the prospects of peace in the whole world.<br><br>
This will mean that the terms of the agreement must be scrupulously adhered to. We shall do everything the agreement requires of us and we shall expect the other parties to do everything it requires of them.  We shall also expect other interested nations to help insure that the agreement is carried out and peace is maintained.<br><br>
PROVISIONS OF THE AGREEMENT <br><br>
Chapter 1: Vietnam National Rights<br><br>
The agreement, as you know, is in nine chapters.  The first affirms the independence, sovereignty, unity and territorial integrity, as recognized by the 1954 Geneva Agreements on Vietnam, agreements which established two zones, divided by a military demarcation line.<br>
....................................................<br><br>
Chapter IV:  Self-determination for South Vietnam<br><br>
Chapter IV of the agreement deals with the right of the South Vietnamese people to self- determination.  Its first provision contains a joint statement by the United States and North Vietnam in which those two countries jointly recognize the South Vietnamese people's right to self-determination, in which those two countries jointly affirm that the South Vietnamese people shall decide for themselves the political system that they shall choose and jointly affirm that no foreign country shall impose any political tendency on the South Vietnamese people.<br><br>
The other principal provision of the agreement are that in implementing the South Vietnamese people's right to self determination, the two South Vietnamese parties will decide, will agree among each other, on free elections, for offices to be decided by the two parties, at a time to be decided by the two parties.  These elections will be supervised and organized first by an institution which has the title of National Council for National Reconciliation and Concord, whose members will be equally appointed by the two sides, which will operate on the principle of unanimity, and which will come into being after negotiation between the two parties, who are obligated by this agreement to do their utmost to bring this institution into being within 90 days.<br><br>
..................................<br><br>
Chapter V Article 15<br><br>
The reunification of Vietnam shall be carried out step by step through peaceful means on the basis of discussion and agreements between North and South Vietnam without coercion or annexation by either party, and without foreign interference.  The time for reunification will be agreed upon by North and South Vietnam.<br><br>
****************************************************<br><br>
The year is 1975.  The military force of the United States has been removed from Vietnam.  The will of the population is against involvement in SouthEast Asia.  I watch the events unfold on T.V.   I have the same feeling expressed in Doc Del's and other's writing about the fall of Saigon.  We saved face in 1973 with the signing of an agreement  that South Vietnam and North Vietnam wouldn't even sign on the same document. That agreement left the South on its own.  But we saved face because we didn't just walk away. The South was suppose to be protected by the agreement.   When the North broke the agreement militarily advancing successfully against the south,   I remembered  back to April through May 1972 when the North attacked the South in a pincher attack which would have cut off where I was stationed from Saigon, with the ultimate goal of the fall of  Saigon.  The women at the hospital were  told we would be evacuated by chopper  in case the North suceeded in breaking through the defenses at Hue.  But, I had also been trained to drive an ambulance to drive patients out;  so,  I didn't really believe that I would be getting on a chopper.  The people trying to flee to safety, the resulting confusion and what we viewed on the news was the enactment of one of my worst fears -  trying to reach transportation out and away from an advancing enemy only to be left behind.  But for me, the defensive lines held and the North was pushed back in what later became known as the Easter offensive.    I can only imagine the feeling of the South Vietnamese in those days leading up to the fall of Saigon and what those who didn't make it out endured.
<p><code>-- (declines to state)  (Betty) </code><p>


